\f0\b \cf2 Answer
\f1\b0 : To answer your questions:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf2 \
1) Yes, it is POSSIBLE for the person on the bottom to escape his head through the other side. However, this "possibility" is determined by the distribution of his weight.\
\
2) I would counter the positioning shown on my instructional with an appropriately timed, "intermediate" level counter. What would that counter be? It would all "depend" on where his weight was at a specific point in time and how his body was positioned in relation to mine (at that specific point in time).\
\
I know that sounds like a vague answer, and it is. However, you must understand that intermediate level Jiu JItsu is so much different than the basic level. Intermediate level Jiu JItsu requires a student to remain aware of a person's weight,  movement and position. Why? Because things can change so quickly.\
\
Also, what looks the same to the beginning level student is not the same to the interiediate level student. Why is that? Simple. The beginning level student is unaware of such things as weight distribution, limb placement and breathing. All the beginning level student can focus on is what he or she sees.\
\
So, even though it might be possible for a beginning level student\cf3  to escape his head through the other side, he would not use this escape against me because I, being a more skilled practitioner, would FEEL his intentions long before he began his escape.\
\
Does that make sense?\
\
Good training to you,\
\
Roy Harris\cf2 \
