\f0\b \cf2 Answer
\f1\b0 : When you boil Jiu Jitsu down to its root, you'll find that the core issue is CONTROL.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf2 \
Whenever you spar with other students, you spend the majority of your time focusing on control. Therefore, it is in your best interest to spend the majority of your time in training focusing on control (rather than the host of other fun topics).\
\
So, to give myself an advantage, I would use a defensive posture to limit my vulnerability and wait for my opponent to engage me. Once I got them to engage me, I could then use my temporary positional advantage to establish control.\
\
Now, when it comes to control, the main area of control is always the hips. I have written many times in my writings that "The person who controls the hips is the person who controls the game." I began writing this back in the mid 1990's and it still applies today.\
\
So, whenever I have the opportunity to HUG an opponent's hips or HUG his thigh, I do so because it gives me an incredible amount of control and makes their response to this control predictable.\
\
NOTICE how I emphasized the word "HUG" in the above paragraph! I did this because I wanted my MALE readers to FOCUS on the word HUG. I also wanted them NOT to read the word GRAB. Why? Because their is a marked difference between a HUG and a GRAB. Why am I emphasizing this with males? Because women naturally understand the word hug - for it means to fully embrace another person with your entire arm and your entire upper body (front side). However, to many males, a hug simply means to grab ahold of someone for a short period of time (and to only use their hands and wrists).\
\
So, to HUG the hips or thigh, one must embrace them with the entire arm and the entire upper body (front side). This means that the hip or thigh will center itself in the crook of your elbow so that it (the elbow) can be pulled towards the center of your body.\
\
Does this make sense?\
\
Good training to you,\
\
Roy Harris\cf0 \
