My follow up response: So you trained Sanuces Ryu Jujutsu? Cool. Whom did you train with? Did you ever meet Professor Moses Powell? I got the chance to train with one of his students, Professor Robert Crosson.\
Since the two of you're are about the same size, here are a few things to try:\
TECHNIQUE #1\
1. When you BEGIN to pull him into your guard, entangle one of his arms with a two on one. In other words, take your right hand and grab his right sleeve at the wrist. Take your left hand and grab the gi just above his right elbow.\
2. Once you have gotten ahold of his gi, pull his hand and elbow across centerline. Don't try and hold it there (because obviously he is very strong). Just try to get him occupied with freeing his arm.\
These two elements will buy you more time.\
Once you have bought more time, you will now have more time to use your feet and your knees to off balance him and set him up for your favorite techniques from the open guard.\
So remember, the moment you BEGIN to pull them into your guard, that's when you entangle his right arm NOT AFTER you have already pulled him into your guard and crossed your ankles.\
TECHNIQUE #2\
1. Once he has stood up in your guard and is beginning to grab at your neck with his left arm, place your right foot on his left hip and push your head to your right. Turn onto your left side as you do so.\
2. With your right hand, push up on his left elbow and turn it over to your left (his right). This will lock his arm and you MAY be able to finish from here. However, at the very least, his focus will not be re- directed towards freeing his left arm instead of placing his right arm in position for the sleeve choke.\
TECHNIQUE #3\
1. Once he has stood up in your guard and has grabbed your neck with both arms, grab ahold of his gi at his shoulders or just above his elbows.\
2. Place both of your feet on his thighs (close to his knees). Walk with your feet and push his knees farther away from you. Your goal is to flatten him out onto his belly.\
3. As he begins to fall onto his belly, violently turn to your right in an effort to sweep him. Sometimes you will get the sweep. Other times he will catch his balance with his hands and will have to start all over again.\
Give these three techniques a try and let me know how it goes.\
Roy Harris\
