Answer: 
\f2\fs25 With regard to the "stiffer muscley base driven elbows tucked in guys", your only hope is to uncross your ankles, move your hips to the side and immediately begin to destroy their neck. This will be the only way you can get them to move their elbows away from their ribs and actually engage you.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural
\cf0 The whole "defensive and athletic game" (that is now prevalent in BJJ) came from wrestlers who were frustrated with Jiu Jitsu. They didn't know how to deal with the legwork of BJJ in an effective manner without exposing their obvious weakness to arm locks and choke. So, they chose to go the defensive route by getting a wide base, tucking in their elbows and chin and waiting until they saw an opportunity to pass the guard or go to a neutral position.\
After they saw how effective this was, very soon after, they began digging their elbows into the inside of the thighs as a method of uncrossing the ankles.\
Shortly thereafter, the Bob Sapp guard pass was born:\
1. Once the ankles were uncross, back away and place both feet on the ground.\
2. Reach under any leg with your right arm.\
3. Explosively throw that leg as far as you can to your left, preferably from one zip code to the next.\
4. Run like Speedy Gonzalez and pass the guard.\
If that didn't work, well, back away and disengage. Wait until you see another opening and then explode past the thrown leg again.\
So, when you have someone who is playing a defensive game with their arms, you have to attack their neck immediately. Push it to the side or place your forearm underneath it and drive it up. Do not allow them to bury their head Shamrock style. Lift it up and force them to use their hands to defend. THIS is how you can get to the elbows!\
Good training to you,\
Roy Harris
